In JavaScript, you can access other class variables using the dot notation to access properties or methods of the class. Here's an example:

```javascript
class Person {
  constructor(name, age) {
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
  }

  getFullName() {
    return this.name;
  }
}

class Employee extends Person {
  constructor(name, age, company) {
    super(name, age);
    this.company = company;
  }

  getEmployeeInfo() {
    return "Name: " + this.name + ", Age: " + this.age + ", Company: " + this.company;
  }
}

// In this example, we're creating an Employee instance and then accessing the name and age properties from the superclass, Person
var employee = new Employee("John Doe", 30, "Acme Corp");
console.log(employee.getFullName());   // Output: "John Doe"
console.log(employee.age);             // Output: 30
```

In this code, we're creating two classes, `Person` and `Employee`. The Employee class extends the Person class, so an instance of the Employee class has access to the properties and methods of the Person class, in addition to its own properties and methods.

To access a property or method of the superclass from a subclass method, you can use the `super` keyword, which refers to the superclass. In the `Employee` class in this example, we're calling the `super(name, age)` constructor method to initialize the `name` and `age` properties of the `Person` superclass. Then, in the `getEmployeeInfo()` method, we're accessing the `name` and `age` properties using the `this` keyword, which refers to the current instance of the `Employee` class.

